hat do Christians do with the Bible? How do theyùindividually and collectivelyùinteract with the sacred texts? Why does this engagement shift so drastically among and between social, historical, religious, and institutional contexts? Such questions are addressed in a most enlightening, engaging, and original way in The Social Life of Scriptures. Contributors offer a collection of closely analyzed and carefully conducted ethnographic and historical case studies, covering a range of geographic, theological, and cultural territory, including: American evangelicals and charismatics; Jamaican Rastafarians; evangelical and Catholic Mayans; Northern Irish charismatics; Nigerian Anglicans; and Chinese evangelicals in the United States. The Social Life of Scriptures is the first book to present an eclectic, cross-cultural, and comparative investigation of Bible use. Moreover, it models an important movement to outline a framework for how scriptures are implicated in organizing social structures and meanings, with specific foci on gender, ethnicity, agency, and power.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aBaron, Akesha1 aBialecki, Jon1 aBielo, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aColeman, Simon1 aHarding, Susan1 aMalley, Brian1 aMurphy, Liam1 aMuse, Erika1 aPinal, Eric Hoenes Del1 aPulis, John1 aRodman, Rosamond1 aSamson, C.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311068861008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertRUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015z978311066331040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780813548418423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780813548418.jpg  a978-3-11-066331-0  RUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-068861-0  RUP Backlist e